        {'title': 'An Inconvenient Truth', 'director': 'Davis Guggenheim', 'year': 2006, 'description': '"An Inconvenient Truth" is a documentary that presents the science of climate change and its potential economic consequences. The film features former Vice President Al Gore as he delivers a slideshow presentation on the evidence of global warming and its impact on the environment and economy. Through data, charts, and personal anecdotes, "An Inconvenient Truth" raises awareness about the urgent need to address climate change and transition to a low-carbon economy.', 'expert_analysis': '"An Inconvenient Truth is a landmark documentary that helped raise global awareness about climate change," says Dr. Kevin Anderson, climate scientist and Deputy Director of the Tyndall Centre for Climate Change Research. "Al Gore\'s powerful presentation of the scientific evidence made climate change a top priority for policymakers and the public."'},
        {'title': 'Before the Flood', 'director': 'Fisher Stevens', 'year': 2016, 'description': '"Before the Flood" is a documentary that follows actor Leonardo DiCaprio as he explores the economic implications of climate change. The film documents DiCaprio\'s journey to various regions around the world affected by global warming, including melting glaciers, deforestation, and rising sea levels. Through interviews with scientists, activists, and world leaders, "Before the Flood" highlights the economic costs of inaction on climate change and the opportunities for renewable energy and sustainable development.', 'expert_analysis': '"Before the Flood is a compelling call to action for climate solutions," says Christiana Figueres, former Executive Secretary of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change. "The film effectively communicates the scientific consensus on climate change and the importance of international cooperation to address this global challenge."'},
        {'title': 'Inside Job', 'director': 'Charles Ferguson', 'year': 2010, 'description': '"Inside Job" is a documentary that investigates the causes of the 2008 global financial crisis. The film examines the role of financial institutions, regulators, and government policies in the economic meltdown that led to the Great Recession. Through interviews with economists, journalists, and Wall Street insiders, "Inside Job" exposes the corruption and conflicts of interest that contributed to the crisis and calls for greater accountability in the financial sector.', 'expert_analysis': '"\'Inside Job\' is a must-watch documentary for anyone who wants to understand the causes of the financial crisis," says  Nouriel  Roubini, economist and professor at New York University. "The film exposes the greed and recklessness on Wall Street that led to the economic meltdown and the need for stricter financial regulations."'},
        {'title': 'The Corporation', 'director': 'Mark Achbar, Jennifer Abbott', 'year': 2003, 'description': '"The Corporation" is a documentary that explores the rise of corporate power and its impact on society and the environment. The film examines the history and legal status of corporations, their influence on politics and culture, and their role in shaping economic policies. Through interviews with corporate executives, activists, and scholars, "The Corporation" raises questions about the ethics and accountability of large corporations and calls for greater regulation to ensure corporate responsibility.', 'expert_analysis': '"\'The Corporation\' is a thought-provoking documentary that challenges us to think critically about the power and influence of corporations," says  Robert  Reich, former U.S. Secretary of Labor and author of "Aftershock: The Future of Economy and Work." "The film raises important questions about corporate accountability and the need for reforms that prioritize social and environmental well-being alongside profit."'},
        {'title': 'Food, Inc.', 'director': 'Robert Kenner', 'year': 2008, 'description': '"Food, Inc." is a documentary that investigates the economic forces behind the industrial food system. The film exposes the practices of multinational corporations that dominate the food industry, including factory farming, genetically modified organisms (GMOs), and unhealthy food products. Through interviews with farmers, activists, and experts, "Food, Inc." raises concerns about the concentration of corporate power in agriculture and its impact on public health, the environment, and food security.', 'expert_analysis': '"Food, Inc. offers a powerful critique of the industrial food system and its negative consequences," says Marion Nestle, a professor of nutrition and public health at New York University and author of "Food Politics." "The film encourages viewers to learn more about where their food comes from and support sustainable and ethical food choices."'},
        {'title': 'The Price of Free', 'director': 'Derek Doneen', 'year': 2018, 'description': '"The Price of Free" (formerly "Kailash") is a documentary that follows Nobel Peace Prize laureate Kailash Satyarthi as he fights against child labor and child slavery. The film documents Satyarthi\'s efforts to rescue children from exploitation and advocate for their rights. Through interviews and footage of Satyarthi\'s work, "The Price of Free" sheds light on the economic cost of cheap labor and the importance of protecting children from harm.', 'expert_analysis': '"\'The Price of Free\' is a powerful call to action against child labor and slavery," says  Kevin Bales,  anti-slavery activist and author of "Fighting Back: How Activists Are Ending Slavery in Our Time." "The film sheds light on the hidden costs of cheap goods and the importance of supporting ethical businesses that prioritize human rights."'},
        {'title': 'Capitalism: A Love Story', 'director': 'Michael Moore', 'year': 2009, 'description': '"Capitalism: A Love Story" is a documentary that examines the economic system of capitalism and its impact on American society. The film explores the influence of corporate interests on politics, the growing gap between the rich and the poor, and the consequences of financial deregulation. Through interviews with workers, homeowners, and experts, "Capitalism: A Love Story" critiques the inequalities and injustices perpetuated by the capitalist system and advocates for economic reform.', 'expert_analysis': '"\'Capitalism: A Love Story\' is a provocative documentary that sparks important conversations about economic inequality and the American Dream," says  Joseph  Stiglitz, Nobel Prize-winning economist and author of "The Price of Inequality." "While Moore\'s approach is critical, the film raises valid concerns about the need for economic policies that promote fairness and shared prosperity."'},
        {'title': 'Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room', 'director': 'Alex Gibney', 'year': 2005, 'description': '"Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room" is a documentary that chronicles the rise and fall of the Enron Corporation, one of the largest corporate scandals in American history. The film examines the fraudulent accounting practices and corporate greed that led to Enron\'s bankruptcy in 2001. Through interviews with former employees, journalists, and government officials, "Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room" exposes the corruption and ethical lapses that contributed to the company\'s collapse.', 'expert_analysis': '"\'Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room\' is a cautionary tale about corporate greed and the dangers of unchecked ambition," says  James  Rickards, economist and author of "Currency Wars." "The film exposes the ethical failures that led to Enron\'s collapse and serves as a reminder of the importance of corporate governance and regulatory oversight."'},
        {'title': 'Super Size Me', 'director': 'Morgan Spurlock', 'year': 2004, 'description': '"Super Size Me" is a documentary that explores the health and economic impact of fast food consumption in the United States. The film follows filmmaker Morgan Spurlock as he eats nothing but McDonald\'s food for 30 days to investigate the effects on his physical and mental health. Through interviews with nutritionists, educators, and policymakers, "Super Size Me" raises concerns about the fast food industry\'s marketing tactics, portion sizes, and contribution to obesity and related health problems.', 'expert_analysis': '"\'Super Size Me\' is a powerful but controversial documentary that highlights the negative health consequences of fast food consumption," says  Kelly  Brownell, public health researcher and Dean of the Yale School of Public Health. "While Spurlock\'s experiment may not be entirely scientific, the film raises important concerns about the marketing of unhealthy foods and the need for healthier options to be readily available."'},
